# RUST Installation

To install Rust, follow these steps:

1. Open a terminal.

2. Run the following command to download and install Rust:

    ```bash
    curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh
    ```

    This command will download the Rust installation script and execute it.

3. Follow the prompts in the terminal to proceed with the installation. You can choose the default options unless you have specific requirements.

4. Once the installation is complete, Rust will be ready to use. You can verify the installation by running the following command:

    ```bash
    rustc --version
    ```

    This command will display the installed version of Rust.

5. Congratulations! You have successfully installed Rust on your system.

For more information and detailed instructions, you can refer to the official Rust documentation: [https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install](https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install)

# Create our first Rust project

To create a new Rust project, follow these steps:

1. Open a terminal.

2. Navigate to the directory where you want to create your project.

3. Run the following command to create a new Rust project:

    ```bash
    cargo new my_project
    ```

    Replace `my_project` with the desired name for your project.

4. Once the project is created, navigate into the project directory:

    ```bash
    cd my_project
    ```

5. Congratulations! You have successfully created your first Rust project.

For more information and detailed instructions on creating and managing Rust projects, you can refer to the official Rust documentation: [https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/)


# Troubleshooting

If you encounter the following error:

```bash
error: could not exec the linker `cc`
```

You can try resolving it by running the following commands:

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install build-essential
```

These commands will update your system's package information and install the necessary build tools.
